{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}} {{Infobox Artwork | title = The Dort | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | image = DortorDordrecht.jpg | artist = [[J. M. W. Turner]] | year = 1818 | medium = Oil on canvas | height_metric = 157.5 | width_metric = 233.7 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | museum = [[Yale Center for British Art]] | city = [[New Haven, CT]] }}
'''''The Dort''''', or '''''Dort or Dordrecht: The Dort packet-boat from Rotterdam becalmed''''' is an 1818 painting by [[J M W Turner]], based on drawings made by him in mid September 1817.<ref>Butlin, Martin, and Evelyn Joll. ''The Paintings of J.M.W. Turner''. New Haven: Published for the Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art and the Tate Gallery by Yale UP, 1984. 103. Print.</ref> It shows a view of the harbour of [[Dordrecht]]. It is the finest example of the influence of Dutch marine painting on Turner's work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3668719/Art-sales-The-man-who-saved-British-art.html|title=Art sales: The man who saved British art|author=Colin Gleadell|date=23 October 2007|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>
It was exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]] in 1818, where it was described by ''[[The Morning Chronicle]]'' as "one of the most magnificent pictures ever exhibited, and does honour to the age". In 1832, [[John Constable]] wrote of the picture, "I remember most of Turner's early works; amongst them one of singular intricacy and beauty; it was a canal with numerous boats making thousands of beautiful shapes, and I think the most complete work of a genius I ever saw".
It was purchased by [[Walter Fawkes]] for 500 guineas at the request of his son, and hung in the drawing room at [[Farnley Hall, North Yorkshire|Farnley Hall]] until it was bought by [[Paul Mellon]] in 1966. It was then donated to the [[Yale Center for British Art]] upon the founding of the centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.britishart.yale.edu/vufind/Record/1667701|title=Dort or Dordrecht: The Dort packet-boat from Rotterdam becalmed}}</ref>
